class Solution {
public:
    bool isSubstringPresent(string s) {
        string rev_s = s;
        reverse(rev_s.begin(), rev_s.end());
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length() - 1; i++) {
            string substr = s.substr(i, 2);
            if (rev_s.find(substr) != string::npos) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates over the input string to check all substrings of length 2, reversing the string once. It uses the `find` method to check if a substring exists in the reversed string, resulting in a linear time complexity overall.
